WEBVTT

00:09.538 --> 00:09.979
Good morning.

00:12.241 --> 00:17.047
We're in the middle of a series that I will tell you.

00:17.067 --> 00:24.777
I don't know how long we will be talking about this, but we are talking about transformation for the foreseeable future.

00:25.858 --> 00:36.432
If you haven't seen them yet, it came to my attention that while I offered them to the children, I never formally invited adults to pick up a bracelet.

00:36.452 --> 00:38.354
If you would like one, it simply says,

00:38.690 --> 00:42.515
transformed, and Southrun Baptist Church on it.

00:42.535 --> 00:43.356
They're in the North X.

00:43.396 --> 00:44.478
We've got a bunch of them, actually.

00:45.098 --> 00:50.486
And my hope is that you are all on this journey with me.

00:51.207 --> 00:55.873
I'm not, well, one, I don't want to be on the journey alone.

00:57.475 --> 01:05.906
But more than that, I don't pretend like I'm at the end of my journey and that I'm just telling you like the way I really do see myself.

01:06.242 --> 01:07.864
on the journey of transformation.

01:07.884 --> 01:11.969
I imagine all of us do, in some respects, or at least should.

01:12.009 --> 01:18.996
And so my hope is, as we are on this journey, we learn some things together.

01:19.016 --> 01:30.930
If there is a deep joy to my job, at least it brings joy to me and fills me with a lot of satisfaction.

01:31.298 --> 01:36.143
is I get to learn things on the job, and specifically about whatever I'm preaching.

01:36.423 --> 01:41.608
So I don't come every Sunday with things that I learned in seminary.

01:41.628 --> 01:47.514
They're usually things that I learned this week, or at least within the last year.

01:47.574 --> 01:54.521
And it's a really lovely part of what I get to do.

01:55.422 --> 01:59.826
And then my hope is for you that it inspires some sort of

02:00.098 --> 02:11.719
journey and learning of your own, that you too might pick up some pieces and pick up your own life and say, yeah, I want more of that, right?

02:12.601 --> 02:24.082
And so as we go through these scriptures over, not just today's scripture, but like next week's and the week's after, I fully anticipate, again, learning alongside of you.

02:24.354 --> 02:39.496
And my hope is that you'll dig in, you'll like embrace the whole transformed theme and that this will become a year of transformation for you personally and corporately for South Run Baptist Church.

02:39.516 --> 02:42.520
It's a deep prayer of mine and something that I've been praying for quite a while.

02:43.662 --> 02:45.585
Speaking of prayer, let's begin with prayer.

02:46.646 --> 02:51.954
Heavenly Father, I come and we come and we give you thanks.

02:53.186 --> 02:54.568
We thank you for your presence.

02:56.410 --> 02:57.312
We thank you for your love.

02:59.114 --> 03:03.901
We thank you for your mercy and forgiveness for reaching out to us.

03:05.924 --> 03:14.415
Many of us come with anxiety or hardship or things swirling in our minds and our hearts.

03:15.697 --> 03:19.402
And Lord, for these moments we ask for peace.

03:21.024 --> 03:22.226
We ask for clarity.

03:22.946 --> 03:27.713
clarity of mind and heart, that we might see you fully, completely.

03:29.094 --> 03:33.641
And Lord, that we might begin the process once again of transformation.

03:34.902 --> 03:37.085
Pray this in Christ's holy name, amen.

03:39.829 --> 03:49.202
In 2008, there was a movie called The Curious Case of Benjamin Button.

03:49.858 --> 03:50.839
Has anyone seen this movie?

03:50.999 --> 03:52.721
The curious case of Benjamin Button.

03:53.682 --> 03:55.244
So it's an odd movie.

03:55.764 --> 03:57.787
I remember watching it long ago.

03:57.827 --> 04:12.963
The premise is simple, if odd, which is that somebody, Benjamin Button, is born an old man and then spends his life getting younger and younger and younger as the movie progresses and his life progresses.

04:13.744 --> 04:19.410
I think this is in large part.

04:19.714 --> 04:24.883
Well, is in part what Paul is trying to say in Ephesians chapter 4.

04:26.406 --> 04:33.238
I try not to get too cute with my titles, but this one feels a little too cute, especially for me.

04:34.100 --> 04:37.787
Anti-aging is like a big thing these days, apparently.

04:38.488 --> 04:40.732
And the women, they put on their creams.

04:40.792 --> 04:44.178
Oh, apparently men do this now too.

04:44.322 --> 04:53.618
And then there's a whole movement out there, if you're not familiar with it, of people who are trying to, of course, live longer and find that fountain of youth.

04:54.520 --> 05:03.315
And I'm afraid they're doing it all wrong, or at least they're not doing it according to the way God would have us do it.

05:03.335 --> 05:09.426
And so I'm gonna offer you what I take to be Paul's anti-aging message.

05:09.570 --> 05:21.590
coming from Ephesians chapter four, perhaps drawing us into the story of Benjamin Button that we too might become young again.

05:21.610 --> 05:36.434
I wanna begin with two claims that will be the claims I'll try to make a few times through this sermon and by the end of which I hope you believe.

05:37.314 --> 05:54.255
The first is by a guy named G.K. Chesterton in a book called Orthodoxy, a chapter titled, The Ethics of Elfland, in which he says, we have sinned and grown old and our father is younger than we.

05:55.657 --> 06:00.302
We have sinned and grown old and our father is younger than we.

06:00.342 --> 06:06.610
Now, if you don't believe Chesterton, and I understand there might be some suspicion here,

06:07.362 --> 06:11.508
My second quote is someone I think you trust a little more.

06:11.548 --> 06:13.570
His name is Jesus.

06:14.792 --> 06:25.767
And in Matthew 18, he says, truly I say to you, unless you turn and become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.

06:26.708 --> 06:31.995
Unless you become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.

06:33.838 --> 06:34.939
All right, let's open up Paul.

06:35.540 --> 06:36.882
I hope you have the

06:37.186 --> 06:48.500
The Bible in front of you, if you don't, there's one in your pew and you're going to want to have it because we're going to read through this somewhat slowly so that you pick up what Paul's putting down.

06:50.683 --> 06:56.310
Chapter four of Ephesians starting verse 17 begins like this.

06:56.470 --> 07:05.842
Now this, I say, and testify in the Lord that you must no longer walk as the Gentiles do in the futility of their minds.

07:06.242 --> 07:17.839
They are darkened in their understanding, alienated from the life of God because of the ignorance that is in them due to their hardness of heart.

07:19.321 --> 07:31.339
Paul begins by attacking a few things here that are in the Gentiles, in case you don't know, he's speaking to an audience of Greeks and Romans primarily.

07:31.359 --> 07:35.986
There might be a few Jews in his audience, but they're likely pagans.

07:36.322 --> 07:39.766
which is to say non-Jews, right?

07:40.387 --> 07:44.151
Christianity is like a very small thing at this point.

07:44.171 --> 07:49.897
And so he's saying to them, look, he's attacking two things, their minds, right?

07:50.158 --> 08:04.594
So he says multiple times, things like they have the futility of their minds, their understanding, their mind is darkened, and they have an ignorance that is about them.

08:04.802 --> 08:15.300
If you think back to, well, Romans 12-2, this idea that the goal is that we are to be transformed in the mind.

08:15.340 --> 08:21.070
Our minds, we are not to be conformed to the world, but be transformed by the renewing of our mind.

08:21.090 --> 08:23.154
So Paul here is

08:23.394 --> 08:34.510
kind of beating that same drum, which is that we've got all of these patterns in our minds, and we've got all of these literal grooves that are up there, as we've talked about in the past.

08:34.530 --> 08:37.494
And the goal is to change those.

08:38.295 --> 08:43.163
And we've got to get out of the old groove and start creating some new patterns.

08:43.723 --> 08:48.370
And so Paul is once again banging this drum, and he's saying that their minds

08:48.642 --> 08:52.628
Well, they are living in a certain form of darkness.

08:53.069 --> 08:55.793
But then he says two things that I find fascinating.

08:56.114 --> 09:05.268
One is that because of this, they are not in the life of God, which in reality is the only life there is, right?

09:05.328 --> 09:08.773
That life, all life, comes from God.

09:09.294 --> 09:13.240
And so if we are not in the life of God, then we're in no life at all.

09:13.661 --> 09:16.946
In fact, if we are apart from the life of God,

09:17.026 --> 09:24.217
Paul's point and Jesus' point and the whole scripture's point is that eventually that thing, it shrivels up and it dies.

09:25.378 --> 09:31.027
And so if we want true life, abundant life, we must find it in God.

09:31.588 --> 09:46.770
But then the second thing, and this is the very end of 18, it goes like this, that all of this is due to the fact that they have a hardness of heart, a hardness

09:47.298 --> 09:47.859
of heart.

09:49.681 --> 09:51.382
Here's something I learned this week.

09:52.404 --> 10:03.376
This word, hardness of heart, it comes from the word perosis, which is a word you might be familiar with if you know the word osteoporosis.

10:04.197 --> 10:10.584
If you know what osteoporosis is, it's the hardening of the bones or it's the making them fragile, right?

10:10.624 --> 10:16.530
It's actually what is, so this picture up here is the

10:17.314 --> 10:20.819
petrified forest, I think it's in Arizona.

10:21.120 --> 10:22.482
Someone correct me if I'm wrong.

10:23.363 --> 10:37.504
And what it is, there's trees that are millions of years old and they become hardened and porous and frail and fragile because of this.

10:39.246 --> 10:47.058
And what is happening is those forests and the hard hearts here have become too

10:47.426 --> 10:50.409
old, they've become too old.

10:52.431 --> 11:16.914
And rather than keeping the heart supple and able to feel things and able to understand the things of God, what has happened to these Gentiles that he's worried about and to his audience that he's speaking to and to you and me is that if we allow our hearts to become a parosis, hardened, frail,

11:18.242 --> 11:23.187
Well, we can no longer feel what God intends us to feel.

11:24.809 --> 11:32.236
If I can just step aside and offer up a deep concern that I have for our entire world.

11:34.138 --> 11:45.490
When I look on social media, a number of months ago, we saw a shooting of Charlie Kirk.

11:46.594 --> 11:51.181
A few weeks ago, we saw a shooting of a woman named Renee Goode.

11:52.202 --> 11:55.708
Just a week and a half ago, we saw a shooting of another man.

11:55.728 --> 12:02.117
And all of this is just streaming into our eyes and our heads as if it's normal.

12:02.878 --> 12:13.234
And my deep fear is that it is creating a hardness of heart that we are all part of, whether we want to be part of it or not.

12:13.698 --> 12:19.864
that we are looking at these things and acting like they are normal and they are not normal.

12:20.985 --> 12:24.248
There's nothing normal about what we are seeing there.

12:26.250 --> 12:30.114
And it doesn't matter what part of the aisle you're on, right?

12:30.534 --> 12:32.917
These terrible things are happening.

12:34.478 --> 12:36.700
And over time we just get used to it.

12:37.501 --> 12:42.386
And my plea to you is don't get used to it.

12:43.106 --> 12:45.710
Don't allow your heart to be hardened.

12:47.012 --> 12:50.657
Keep your hearts supple and soft.

12:52.100 --> 12:55.284
All three of the people that I mentioned were children of God.

12:56.086 --> 13:01.594
These are three people who are God's beloved and who have been taken from this earth.

13:03.337 --> 13:08.184
That is a terrible thing.

13:08.204 --> 13:12.210
The plea of the whole day, of this whole sermon,

13:12.354 --> 13:21.568
that we keep our hearts supple, and that we not allow them to grow old, and that we find a way to be young again.

13:21.588 --> 13:40.818
If we keep reading, in verse 19, Paul goes on, he says, they, our hearts, have become calloused, and they, the people, have given themselves up to sensuality, greedy to practice every kind of impurity,

13:40.962 --> 13:44.887
But this is not the way you learned in Christ.

13:46.769 --> 13:54.879
Paul says that the hardness or calluses on the heart have allowed people to do that which they should not do.

13:56.060 --> 14:00.646
And he names a few things, specifically sensuality, maybe lust, right?

14:00.706 --> 14:02.508
Or greed.

14:02.548 --> 14:10.738
But any kind of impurity is his last category there, which is to say anything at all.

14:11.074 --> 14:16.102
that is apart from, again, the way you learned in Christ.

14:17.023 --> 14:25.476
Well, when you do those things, when you behave in that kind of way, one of two things happens.

14:26.358 --> 14:39.698
Your conscience is pricked and you change your way, or you keep doing that thing and you build up calluses so that your conscience can no longer be pricked.

14:42.018 --> 15:06.075
I implore you, allow it to be, soften your heart, that whatever that impurity is, whether it's lust, greed, or anything, that you allow God in there to do the work that needs to be done, to rip off those calluses and to find yourself changing once again.

15:06.135 --> 15:10.802
Paul continues.

15:12.034 --> 15:23.909
And he says this, assuming you have heard about Jesus and were taught in him as the truth is actually in Jesus.

15:23.969 --> 15:40.370
And now he gets to the three verses that got me to this passage at all, which is to say to put off your old self, which belongs to your former manner of life and is corrupt through deceitful desires.

15:41.666 --> 16:00.270
And here again, this is kind of the second piece in the foundation of my argument that we are old and we need to get young again, that we've gotten too old in life and too hardened and that the osteoporosis has set in on our hearts of all places.

16:01.732 --> 16:06.458
And he says here that we need to get rid of the old self to put it off.

16:07.339 --> 16:10.002
And this word old, I've always taken to mean

16:10.082 --> 16:13.207
are former selves, the self who we were.

16:13.227 --> 16:15.370
And it does mean that too, just so we're clear.

16:16.251 --> 16:18.514
But the word is actually old.

16:19.276 --> 16:23.322
It's ancient, it's the things long ago, right?

16:23.742 --> 16:29.771
And so the old self is the person who has become too old.

16:29.851 --> 16:31.674
And so then he says, what next?

16:31.774 --> 16:39.826
Well, what we're supposed to do, well, in verse 23, we need to be renewed in the spirit of our minds.

16:40.450 --> 16:41.451
renewed.

16:41.872 --> 16:45.896
This word is used once in all of the New Testament right here.

16:47.017 --> 16:56.748
And it simply means to be made young again, to be made young again, renewed.

16:58.911 --> 17:05.458
And so Paul is saying, you had this old self, and now we need to be made young again.

17:07.458 --> 17:09.540
And he says, well, how do we do this?

17:09.560 --> 17:23.335
Well, in the spirit of our minds, the spirit, this is an odd phrase that Paul uses because there is a spirit and there's a mind and these are usually two different things and the mind doesn't typically have a spirit.

17:23.856 --> 17:25.437
And so here's what I think he's saying.

17:25.477 --> 17:33.426
In the posture of like the way you think about things, I need you to be young again.

17:33.762 --> 17:37.226
I need you to think like a little kid thinks.

17:37.906 --> 17:40.249
And I need you to be curious in the world.

17:40.629 --> 17:52.902
And I need you to have open eyes to the possibility of what is out there and not to be closed off to what you assume the world is like and what your neighbor is like.

17:54.183 --> 18:01.170
And I need you to have a posture of mind, a spirit of mind that is once again made young.

18:02.370 --> 18:07.096
And then the third part of his three-part sermon here is verse 24.

18:07.657 --> 18:17.831
We must put on the new self, which is created after the likeness of God in true righteousness and holiness.

18:20.455 --> 18:23.459
The likeness of God, the likeness of God.

18:24.800 --> 18:31.890
I kept reading that and thinking, I bet Paul has in mind

18:32.290 --> 18:33.872
Genesis 1, 26.

18:35.194 --> 18:43.125
When we two were created, when we were created in the likeness of God.

18:46.549 --> 18:53.679
And in fact, what he may be saying, I think he is, is something of a paradox.

18:54.740 --> 19:01.810
You see, there is the old self, and the old self is indeed, well, it's old.

19:02.530 --> 19:07.176
It's become hard-hearted, and osteoporosis has set in right here.

19:07.196 --> 19:26.901
But there's actually an older self yet, the one from the foundations of the world, the way in which he created all of us to be, created how, in the likeness of God, in God's image, we were created.

19:26.921 --> 19:30.866
And this is how it was all supposed to work from the beginning.

19:31.394 --> 19:41.183
Until what happened, Genesis 1 turns to Genesis 2 and 3 and sin sets in and the heart turns to stone.

19:43.425 --> 19:55.056
So Paul is saying to us, we indeed, as Chesterton says, have sinned and grown old and our father is younger than we.

19:56.337 --> 20:01.362
Or as Jesus says, I say to you, unless you turn and become like children,

20:01.666 --> 20:04.810
you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.

20:08.395 --> 20:12.721
Okay, so maybe, maybe you're ready to believe that this is true.

20:12.741 --> 20:16.507
I might have some convincing left to do.

20:17.628 --> 20:21.534
But the next question always is, Eric, how do we do that?

20:22.375 --> 20:22.775
How?

20:23.456 --> 20:25.279
How do we become young again?

20:25.339 --> 20:30.546
There is a hard way and an easy way

20:31.618 --> 20:34.621
And the easy way happens to also be a hard way.

20:36.263 --> 20:37.304
We'll start with the hard.

20:39.046 --> 20:39.887
We'll start with the hard.

20:41.048 --> 20:50.278
A few weeks, well, the week and a half, just over a week ago, I was in Waco, Texas with my son.

20:50.318 --> 20:51.619
We were at Baylor's campus.

20:51.719 --> 20:56.544
And I caught up with a woman who entered the PhD program when I did.

20:57.045 --> 20:58.386
We went through it together.

20:58.530 --> 21:05.757
She has had a little more academic success than I have, and she is now working there, and she's doing very well.

21:06.398 --> 21:09.941
And we talked about one of our professors, Dr. Talbert.

21:10.842 --> 21:13.365
Dr. Talbert was a hard and a harsh man.

21:14.246 --> 21:17.509
He was known for being able to make grown men cry.

21:17.529 --> 21:26.898
He was taxing, he was very difficult, and he made my life

21:27.074 --> 21:28.816
very difficult in those years.

21:29.857 --> 21:44.735
Alicia, my friend, and I were talking about Dr. Talbert, and she told me this story that broke my heart, and again, epitomizes what I take to be the hard way.

21:47.359 --> 21:53.906
About a year or two after I finished the program and had left, Dr. Talbert had a stroke.

21:55.088 --> 21:56.850
He nearly died, but he did not die.

21:57.186 --> 21:59.389
In fact, he lived for 10 more years after that.

22:01.231 --> 22:14.827
Alicia informs me that his daughter is so appreciative for those 10 years after the stroke because according to her, his daughter said for the first time in her life she had a dad.

22:18.232 --> 22:23.538
Something happened to Dr. Talper in that stroke to cause him to wake up.

22:24.514 --> 22:34.105
and to soften whatever was going on here, and to recognize he needed to live a very different kind of life.

22:34.125 --> 22:41.293
That, my friends, is the hard way, and I hope you don't have to learn the hard way how to soften this.

22:43.015 --> 22:44.337
Let me offer you the easy way.

22:46.419 --> 22:50.043
The easy way, again, is not easy.

22:50.083 --> 22:52.466
It to is hard.

22:53.410 --> 22:58.856
but it begins with the recognition that something's wrong and you need to change.

22:59.517 --> 23:14.353
And so the easy way might look something like this, a recognition of what the old us looks like and what the young us could look like or should look like.

23:15.995 --> 23:22.642
By the way, when I say old, here's how I understand this to work.

23:24.226 --> 23:26.550
Something happens in childhood.

23:26.570 --> 23:37.306
And there's, I can't put like an exact year on this, but where you move from childhood into, we'll say like adolescence.

23:37.326 --> 23:41.933
And it's at this point that the hardness kind of starts to creep in.

23:41.973 --> 23:48.082
And then from there, it only gets harder, but

23:48.386 --> 24:06.434
It's not to say it's like a one-way street because I meet many folks, you and outside of this church, who are aging in a way that is beautiful and good and recognizes the suppleness of your heart.

24:07.355 --> 24:17.170
And I think to myself, this person, despite being older in age than other peers that I have or people who are younger than me,

24:17.538 --> 24:24.268
This person, they appear younger and healthier and more vibrant.

24:25.450 --> 24:26.812
And so this is what we're going for.

24:26.912 --> 24:29.316
It's not about a numerical age of oldness.

24:30.057 --> 24:31.179
It's about what's in here.

24:32.201 --> 24:32.942
So it looks like this.

24:33.783 --> 24:46.162
The old heart is filled with certainty, certainty about the world, the way it works, who does what, the good guys and the bad guys, the people that are around them,

24:46.434 --> 24:55.147
Certainly your spouse and all of their flaws and their problems, maybe some of their goodness too, but they're certain of all this.

24:57.470 --> 25:01.997
The young of heart, the young is curious.

25:03.600 --> 25:16.018
No matter how long they've known this person or this world, they keep their eyes open, ready to be surprised, surprised by what their spouse might do or say.

25:16.610 --> 25:20.776
surprised by what the world may offer in all the best kind of ways.

25:21.657 --> 25:32.372
They have a certain realism about them, but a realism that also hopes and has an optimism about what the world might do.

25:35.777 --> 25:40.363
The old heart, well, it looks on the world with suspicion.

25:40.423 --> 25:45.170
Always ready for something to go wrong.

25:45.922 --> 25:47.324
They live guarded lives.

25:48.325 --> 25:50.909
They've probably been hurt more than a few times.

25:51.710 --> 25:53.593
They want to make sure that doesn't happen again.

25:54.494 --> 25:56.156
And so they build walls around it.

25:56.957 --> 26:00.382
They cut themselves off from anything that might hurt them.

26:01.684 --> 26:07.131
But the young, the young heart, it still trusts.

26:07.151 --> 26:15.122
It trusts, just like the young person, that there's just going to be food in the refrigerator no matter what happens, right?

26:15.266 --> 26:25.302
or they trust that whoever comes along and picks them up and that they're a good person and that they're safe in their arms, they trust.

26:27.205 --> 26:30.811
The young heart is able to trust.

26:33.175 --> 26:42.610
The old heart is filled with inhibition, afraid to get on the dance floor because they're afraid of what other people might think.

26:42.786 --> 26:46.291
What would this other person say?

26:46.311 --> 26:55.504
And they put up walls again around them in order to keep them safe from the judgment of others because they're not so sure what others might think.

26:56.686 --> 27:05.298
But the little ones, the young at Har, they live with abandon and they trust others.

27:05.890 --> 27:08.414
that this is a non-judgmental space.

27:08.474 --> 27:11.859
And if somebody does judge them, well, that's their problem.

27:12.059 --> 27:13.401
Why would they do such a thing?

27:16.346 --> 27:17.087
The old heart.

27:18.849 --> 27:22.955
It is much like my own, unfortunately, too often.

27:22.975 --> 27:28.103
It is all about efficiency, getting from one place to the next quickly.

27:28.123 --> 27:35.474
And with purpose, always in a rush, because there's always a lot to do.

27:36.226 --> 27:38.790
There's too much to do.

27:38.810 --> 27:47.362
If you've ever had children under the age of five and you've tried to get them to church in the morning, efficiency is nowhere on the radar.

27:48.184 --> 27:50.267
They live an unhurried life.

27:51.789 --> 27:57.718
They are casually walking about this world, enjoying every moment of it.

27:58.819 --> 28:03.506
Until mom or dad comes along and says, hurry up, get your shoes on, we've got to get to church.

28:06.754 --> 28:13.422
an unhurried life is a beautiful thing.

28:13.442 --> 28:25.738
I think there's a way in which the youngest among us can teach us so much about how to grow older in ways that we've somehow lost.

28:29.162 --> 28:35.730
Transformation looks a lot like putting some of the old self behind

28:36.066 --> 28:40.772
and embracing the young self.

28:40.792 --> 28:47.141
Paul also talks more specifically about sin and what this looks like.

28:47.301 --> 28:53.249
And so if you want to read 25 to 32, you'll find the following things in there.

28:53.289 --> 29:03.122
And he'll say that the old heart looks like somebody who tells falsehoods and lies, but the new heart or the young heart, well, they tell the truth.

29:03.938 --> 29:12.829
The old heart is filled with sinful anger, but the young heart tries to resolve things before the sundown.

29:14.390 --> 29:25.003
The old heart it takes doesn't give back, but the new or the young heart is working in order to share with others.

29:26.305 --> 29:30.930
The old heart is filled with corrupt and toxic talk.

29:31.810 --> 29:36.655
while the young heart builds others up and speaks life into others.

29:38.677 --> 29:47.766
And lastly, he says that the old heart, well, it has bitterness, wrath, anger, clamor, and slander on its lips.

29:49.428 --> 29:59.698
But the young heart, the new heart, filled with kindness, it is tender-hearted, that's Paul's word, tender-hearted and forgiving.

30:01.282 --> 30:09.673
The questions you're now left with include the following, diagnosis questions, what calluses do you have on your heart?

30:10.334 --> 30:12.296
Where have you grown old?

30:13.077 --> 30:15.360
Where have you grown unfeeling?

30:16.922 --> 30:29.298
Paul offers us in his letter two categories, the categories of sin, maybe it's lust or greed or any impurity that you've grown accustomed to.

30:29.698 --> 30:32.222
And it's time to rip that callus off of your heart.

30:34.004 --> 30:51.349
Or it could look like personal things, the way you treat other people, lying to others, excessive anger, taking instead of giving corrupts or toxic talk, bitterness, wrath, anger, or clamor.

30:53.111 --> 30:55.274
So it starts with the diagnosis of yourself.

30:55.855 --> 30:57.938
What's going on in here?

30:58.178 --> 30:59.740
Where have I gone wrong?

31:00.241 --> 31:03.526
And where do I need God to pierce the hardness?

31:04.848 --> 31:06.170
And then comes the cure.

31:06.210 --> 31:10.316
The cure, well, this is the part that maybe is the hardest.

31:10.356 --> 31:13.421
And I wish I had like clear cut answers for you.

31:14.703 --> 31:19.270
But you have to answer somehow, how will you become young again?

31:19.290 --> 31:21.853
How will you soften your heart?

31:22.534 --> 31:27.602
How will you renew the spirit of your mind or the posture of your mind?

31:28.450 --> 31:42.067
I assure you, it involves curiosity and trust and abandon and becoming unhurried because we have sinned and grown old and our father is younger than we.

31:42.107 --> 31:50.598
But truly, I say to you, unless you turn and become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.

31:51.659 --> 31:52.140
Let's pray.

31:55.765 --> 31:56.946
God, our Father in heaven,

31:57.890 --> 32:01.795
We are your children, and yet somehow we have grown old.

32:03.958 --> 32:14.412
We have allowed the things of this world, oftentimes the things that have hurt us and that we are guarding against to harden our hearts.

32:16.956 --> 32:27.730
God, show us a better way, a way in which we can become young again, filled with curiosity and hope and optimism

32:28.258 --> 32:32.362
about ourselves and others, and what is possible in this world.

32:33.063 --> 32:40.731
That you are redeeming this place, and restoring it, and that we, we are to be part of that process.

32:44.936 --> 32:50.542
God, I give you thanks for Salfram Baptist Church, and for each person in this room.

32:50.562 --> 32:55.527
As a journey toward transformation, may you show them the way.

32:56.348 --> 32:58.130
In Christ's name we pray, amen.

33:00.354 --> 33:00.695
Friends.

